@hariharans29 I'm using the CUDA one. Following is a list of onnx related packages and the version numbers installed with pip:
```
onnx                1.10.2
```

issue.title: Fix a bug in ReluClip fusion

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: 

`Graph::AddInitializedTensor()` doesn't create a NodeArg for the TensorProto if the graph is loaded from a model file (even if it doesn't exist in the graph).
 
See here-
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/ac57afc3a69dfc6a57caeee678966a1fce50bca9/onnxruntime/core/graph/graph.cc#L2790

The call to `AddInitializedTensor()` from the ReluClip fusion optimizer breaks the OP's model in #9753 because the graph is loaded from a model file and hence the initialized tensor added to the graph is left without a corresponding NodeArg by the logic pasted above.
 
The test added in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2059/ does emulate the model but the NodeArg does end up getting created in that instance as the graph is not loaded from a model file.

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve #9753

issue.title: Runtime Exception when relu is followed by a clip

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body: @hariharans29 **Describe the bug** Similar to #9753, on opset version 14, when relu is followed by a clip ```clip(relu(i1),-1,1)```, and input ```i1``` is ```torch.float64``` data type, ORT raises a RuntimeException Error. **Urgency** None. **System information** - OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): macOS Mojave - ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Binary - ONNX Runtime version: 1.10.0 - Python version: 3.9.7 - Visual Studio version (if applicable): n/a - GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): n/a - CUDA/cuDNN version: n/a - GPU model and memory: n/a - PyTorch version: 1.10.2 **To Reproduce** - Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior. ``` import torch import onnx.checker import onnxruntime as ort class Model(torch.nn.Module): @torch.no_grad() def forward(self, i1): x=torch.relu(i1) o0=torch.clip(x,-1,1) return o0 model = Model() inputs = (torch.randn((2, 2, 2, 1, 2),dtype=torch.float64),) output_names = ["o0"] torch.onnx.export(model, inputs, "1.onnx", verbose=False, input_names=["i1"], output_names=output_names, opset_version=14) onnx_model = onnx.load("1.onnx") onnx.checker.check_model(onnx_model,full_check=True) sess = ort.InferenceSession( onnx._serialize(onnx_model)) res = sess.run(output_names, {"input": inputs[0].numpy()}) ``` - Attach the ONNX model to the issue (where applicable) to expedite investigation. [1.onnx.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/8301462/1.onnx.zip) **Expected behavior** Not crash. **Screenshots** - Error message
